PROMPT eventual_consistency_explanation
WITH BUDGET 8000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a distributed systems architect specializing in consistency models, consensus algorithms, and the fundamental trade-offs between consistency, availability, and partition tolerance in distributed computing environments.")

GENERATE
    explain_consistency_models("Explain eventual consistency in distributed systems and how it differs from strong consistency, covering: the definition of eventual consistency as a consistency model where the system guarantees that if no new updates are made to a given data item, eventually all accesses to that item will return the last updated value, meaning all replicas will converge to the same state given enough time without concurrent updates, the key characteristics including temporary inconsistencies are allowed where different nodes may return different values for the same data at any given moment, convergence guarantee that all replicas will eventually agree on the same value, and no guarantees about when convergence will occur or the order in which updates propagate, contrast with strong consistency models including linearizability where operations appear to execute atomically and in real-time order, sequential consistency where operations appear to execute in some global sequential order consistent with program order, and strict serializability where transactions appear to execute atomically in a global order consistent with their real-time ordering, practical implications of eventual consistency such as applications must handle temporary inconsistencies gracefully, users may see stale or conflicting data temporarily, system remains available during network partitions, and provides better performance and scalability compared to strong consistency, real-world examples including DNS propagation where changes take time to propagate globally, social media feeds where likes and comments may appear inconsistent across users, distributed caches like Redis clusters, Amazon DynamoDB default consistency model, and collaborative editing systems like Google Docs, the CAP theorem context explaining how eventual consistency prioritizes availability and partition tolerance over consistency, allowing systems to remain operational during network failures, conflict resolution mechanisms including last-write-wins policies, vector clocks for causal ordering, CRDTs (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types) that automatically merge concurrent updates, and application-level conflict resolution strategies, implementation techniques such as gossip protocols for peer-to-peer propagation, read repair mechanisms that fix inconsistencies during read operations, anti-entropy processes that periodically synchronize replicas, and quorum-based systems like Amazon's Dynamo, trade-offs analysis covering when to choose eventual consistency for high availability requirements, geographic distribution needs, and performance-critical applications versus when strong consistency is required for financial transactions, inventory management, and systems where inconsistency has severe consequences, and best practices for designing applications with eventual consistency including idempotent operations, conflict resolution strategies, user interface design that accounts for temporary inconsistencies, and monitoring tools to track convergence times and detect prolonged inconsistencies.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 4000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;